# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: spacy-nlp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The notion of dependencies between grammatical units has existed since the earliest recorded grammars, e.g.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Pāṇini, and the dependency concept therefore arguably predates that of phrase structure by many centuries.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Ibn Maḍāʾ, a 12th-century linguist from Córdoba, Andalusia, may have been the first grammarian to use the term *dependency* in the grammatical sense that we use it today.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] In early modern times, the dependency concept seems to have coexisted side by side with that of phrase structure, the latter having entered Latin, French, English and other grammars from the widespread study of term logic of antiquity.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Dependency is also concretely present in the works of Sámuel Brassai (1800–1897), a Hungarian linguist, Franz Kern (1830–1894), a German philologist, and of Heimann Hariton Tiktin (1850–1936), a Romanian linguist.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Modern dependency grammars, however, begin primarily with the work of Lucien Tesnière.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Tesnière was a Frenchman, a polyglot, and a professor of linguistics at the universities in Strasbourg and Montpellier.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] His major work *Éléments de syntaxe structurale* was published posthumously in 1959 – he died in 1954.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The basic approach to syntax he developed has at least partially influenced the work of others in the 1960s, although it is not clear in what way these works were inspired by other sources.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] A number of other dependency-based grammars have gained prominence since those early works.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] DG has generated a lot of interest in Germany in both theoretical syntax and language pedagogy.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] In recent years, the great development surrounding dependency-based theories has come from computational linguistics and is due, in part, to the influential work that David Hays did in machine translation at the RAND Corporation in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Dependency-based systems are increasingly being used to parse natural language and generate tree banks.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Interest in dependency grammar is growing at present, international conferences on dependency linguistics being a relatively recent development (Depling 2011, Depling 2013, Depling 2015, Depling 2017, Depling 2019 Archived 2019-03-06 at the Wayback Machine).
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Dependency is a one-to-one correspondence: for every element (e.g. word or morph) in the sentence, there is exactly one node in the structure of that sentence that corresponds to that element.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The result of this one-to-one correspondence is that dependency grammars are word (or morph) grammars.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] All that exist are the elements and the dependencies that connect the elements into a structure.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] This situation should be compared with phrase structure.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Phrase structure is a one-to-one-or-more correspondence, which means that, for every element in a sentence, there are one or more nodes in the structure that correspond to that element.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The result of this difference is that dependency structures are minimal compared to their phrase structure counterparts, since they tend to contain many fewer nodes.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] These trees illustrate two possible ways to render the dependency and phrase structure relations (see below).
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] This dependency tree is an "ordered" tree, i.e. it reflects actual word order.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Many dependency trees abstract away from linear order and focus just on hierarchical order, which means they do not show actual word order.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] This constituency (= phrase structure) tree follows the conventions of bare phrase structure (BPS), whereby the words themselves are employed as the node labels.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The distinction between dependency and phrase structure grammars derives in large part from the initial division of the clause.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The phrase structure relation derives from an initial binary division, whereby the clause is split into a subject noun phrase (NP) and a predicate verb phrase (VP).
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] This division is certainly present in the basic analysis of the clause that we find in the works of, for instance, Leonard Bloomfield and Noam Chomsky.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Tesnière, however, argued vehemently against this binary division, preferring instead to position the verb as the root of all clause structure.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Tesnière's stance was that the subject-predicate division stems from term logic and has no place in linguistics.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Link grammar is similar to dependency grammar, but link grammar does not include directionality between the linked words, and thus does not describe head-dependent relationships.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Hybrid dependency/phrase structure grammar uses dependencies between words, but also includes dependencies between phrasal nodes – see for example the Quranic Arabic Dependency Treebank.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The derivation trees of tree-adjoining grammar are dependency structures, although the full trees of TAG rendered in terms of phrase structure, so in this regard, it is not clear whether TAG should be viewed more as a dependency or phrase structure grammar.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] There are major differences between the grammars just listed.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] In this regard, the dependency relation is compatible with other major tenets of theories of grammar.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Thus like phrase structure grammars, dependency grammars can be mono- or multistratal, representational or derivational, construction- or rule-based.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] There are various conventions that DGs employ to represent dependencies.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The representations in (a–d) are trees, whereby the specific conventions employed in each tree vary.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Solid lines are *dependency edges* and lightly dotted lines are *projection lines*.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The only difference between tree (a) and tree (b) is that tree (a) employs the category class to label the nodes whereas tree (b) employs the words themselves as the node labels.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Tree (c) is a reduced tree insofar as the string of words below and projection lines are deemed unnecessary and are hence omitted.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Tree (d) abstracts away from linear order and reflects just hierarchical order.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The arrow arcs in (e) are an alternative convention used to show dependencies and are favored by Word Grammar.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The brackets in (f) are seldom used, but are nevertheless quite capable of reflecting the dependency hierarchy; dependents appear enclosed in more brackets than their heads.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] And finally, the indentations like those in (g) are another convention that is sometimes employed to indicate the hierarchy of words.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Dependents are placed underneath their heads and indented.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Like tree (d), the indentations in (g) abstract away from linear order.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The point to these conventions is that they are just that, namely conventions.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] They do not influence the basic commitment to dependency as the relation that is grouping syntactic units.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The dependency representations above (and further below) show syntactic dependencies.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Indeed, most work in dependency grammar focuses on syntactic dependencies.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Syntactic dependencies are, however, just one of three or four types of dependencies.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Meaning–text theory, for instance, emphasizes the role of semantic and morphological dependencies in addition to syntactic dependencies.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] A fourth type, prosodic dependencies, can also be acknowledged.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Distinguishing between these types of dependencies can be important, in part because if one fails to do so, the likelihood that semantic, morphological, and/or prosodic dependencies will be mistaken for syntactic dependencies is great.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The following four subsections briefly sketch each of these dependency types.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] During the discussion, the existence of syntactic dependencies is taken for granted and used as an orientation point for establishing the nature of the other three dependency types.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Semantic dependencies are understood in terms of predicates and their arguments.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The arguments of a predicate are semantically dependent on that predicate.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Often, semantic dependencies overlap with and point in the same direction as syntactic dependencies.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] At times, however, semantic dependencies can point in the opposite direction of syntactic dependencies, or they can be entirely independent of syntactic dependencies.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The two arguments *Sam* and *Sally* in tree (a) are dependent on the predicate *likes*, whereby these arguments are also syntactically dependent on *likes*.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] What this means is that the semantic and syntactic dependencies overlap and point in the same direction (down the tree).
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Attributive adjectives, however, are predicates that take their head noun as their argument, hence *big* is a predicate in tree (b) that takes *bones* as its one argument; the semantic dependency points up the tree and therefore runs counter to the syntactic dependency.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] A similar situation obtains in (c), where the preposition predicate *on* takes the two arguments *the picture* and *the wall*; one of these semantic dependencies points up the syntactic hierarchy, whereas the other points down it.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Finally, the predicate *to help* in (d) takes the one argument *Jim* but is not directly connected to *Jim* in the syntactic hierarchy, which means that semantic dependency is entirely independent of the syntactic dependencies.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Morphological dependencies obtain between words or parts of words.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] When a given word or part of a word influences the form of another word, then the latter is morphologically dependent on the former.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Agreement and concord are therefore manifestations of morphological dependencies.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Like semantic dependencies, morphological dependencies can overlap with and point in the same direction as syntactic dependencies, overlap with and point in the opposite direction of syntactic dependencies, or be entirely independent of syntactic dependencies.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The arrows are now used to indicate morphological dependencies.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The plural *houses* in (a) demands the plural of the demonstrative determiner, hence *these* appears, not *this*, which means there is a morphological dependency that points down the hierarchy from *houses* to *these*.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The situation is reversed in (b), where the singular subject *Sam* demands the appearance of the agreement suffix *-s* on the finite verb *works*, which means there is a morphological dependency pointing up the hierarchy from *Sam* to *works*.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The type of determiner in the German examples (c) and (d) influences the inflectional suffix that appears on the adjective *alt*.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] When the indefinite article *ein* is used, the strong masculine ending *-er* appears on the adjective.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] When the definite article *der* is used, in contrast, the weak ending *-e* appears on the adjective.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Thus since the choice of determiner impacts the morphological form of the adjective, there is a morphological dependency pointing from the determiner to the adjective, whereby this morphological dependency is entirely independent of the syntactic dependencies.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The masculine subject *le chien* in (a) demands the masculine form of the predicative adjective *blanc*, whereas the feminine subject *la maison* demands the feminine form of this adjective.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] A morphological dependency that is entirely independent of the syntactic dependencies therefore points again across the syntactic hierarchy.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Morphological dependencies play an important role in typological studies.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Languages are classified as mostly head-marking (*Sam work-s*) or mostly dependent-marking (*these houses*), whereby most if not all languages contain at least some minor measure of both head and dependent marking.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Prosodic dependencies are acknowledged in order to accommodate the behavior of clitics.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] A clitic is a syntactically autonomous element that is prosodically dependent on a host.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] A clitic is therefore integrated into the prosody of its host, meaning that it forms a single word with its host.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Prosodic dependencies exist entirely in the linear dimension (horizontal dimension), whereas standard syntactic dependencies exist in the hierarchical dimension (vertical dimension).
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Classic examples of clitics in English are reduced auxiliaries (e.g.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] A given clitic is often prosodically dependent on its syntactic dependent (*He'll*, *There's*) or on its head (*would've*).
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] At other times, it can depend prosodically on a word that is neither its head nor its immediate dependent (*Florida's*).
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Syntactic dependencies are the focus of most work in DG, as stated above.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] How the presence and the direction of syntactic dependencies are determined is of course often open to debate.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] In this regard, it must be acknowledged that the validity of syntactic dependencies in the trees throughout this article is being taken for granted.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] However, these hierarchies are such that many DGs can largely support them, although there will certainly be points of disagreement.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The basic question about how syntactic dependencies are discerned has proven difficult to answer definitively.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] One should acknowledge in this area, however, that the basic task of identifying and discerning the presence and direction of the syntactic dependencies of DGs is no easier or harder than determining the constituent groupings of phrase structure grammars.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Etymological considerations also provide helpful clues about the direction of dependencies.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] A promising principle upon which to base the existence of syntactic dependencies is distribution.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] When one is striving to identify the root of a given phrase, the word that is most responsible for determining the distribution of that phrase as a whole is its root.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Traditionally, DGs have had a different approach to linear order (word order) than phrase structure grammars.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Dependency structures are minimal compared to their phrase structure counterparts, and these minimal structures allow one to focus intently on the two ordering dimensions.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Separating the vertical dimension (hierarchical order) from the horizontal dimension (linear order) is easily accomplished.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] This aspect of dependency structures has allowed DGs, starting with Tesnière (1959), to focus on hierarchical order in a manner that is hardly possible for phrase structure grammars.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] For Tesnière, linear order was secondary to hierarchical order insofar as hierarchical order preceded linear order in the mind of a speaker.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The stemmas (trees) that Tesnière produced reflected this view; they abstracted away from linear order to focus almost entirely on hierarchical order.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Many DGs that followed Tesnière adopted this practice, that is, they produced tree structures that reflect hierarchical order alone, e.g.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The traditional focus on hierarchical order generated the impression that DGs have little to say about linear order, and it has contributed to the view that DGs are particularly well-suited to examine languages with free word order.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] A negative result of this focus on hierarchical order, however, is that there is a dearth of DG explorations of particular word order phenomena, such as of standard discontinuities.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Comprehensive dependency grammar accounts of topicalization, *wh*-fronting, scrambling, and extraposition are mostly absent from many established DG frameworks.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] This situation can be contrasted with phrase structure grammars, which have devoted tremendous effort to exploring these phenomena.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The nature of the dependency relation does not, however, prevent one from focusing on linear order.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Dependency structures are as capable of exploring word order phenomena as phrase structures.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The following trees illustrate this point; they represent one way of exploring discontinuities using dependency structures.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The trees suggest the manner in which common discontinuities can be addressed.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The a-trees on the left show projectivity violations (= crossing lines), and the b-trees on the right demonstrate one means of addressing these violations.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The displaced constituent takes on a word as its head that is not its governor.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The words in red mark the catena (=chain) of words that extends from the root of the displaced constituent to the governor of that constituent.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Discontinuities are then explored in terms of these catenae.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The limitations on topicalization, *wh*-fronting, scrambling, and extraposition can be explored and identified by examining the nature of the catenae involved.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Traditionally, DGs have treated the syntactic functions (= grammatical functions, grammatical relations) as primitive.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] They posit an inventory of functions (e.g. subject, object, oblique, determiner, attribute, predicative, etc.).
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] These functions can appear as labels on the dependencies in the tree structures, e.g.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The syntactic functions in this tree are shown in green: ATTR (attribute), COMP-P (complement of preposition), COMP-TO (complement of to), DET (determiner), P-ATTR (prepositional attribute), PRED (predicative), SUBJ (subject), TO-COMP (to complement).
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The functions chosen and abbreviations used in the tree here are merely representative of the general stance of DGs toward the syntactic functions.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The actual inventory of functions and designations employed vary from DG to DG.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] As a primitive of the theory, the status of these functions is very different from that in some phrase structure grammars.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Traditionally, phrase structure grammars derive the syntactic functions from the constellation.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] For instance, the object is identified as the NP appearing inside finite VP, and the subject as the NP appearing outside of finite VP.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Since DGs reject the existence of a finite VP constituent, they were never presented with the option to view the syntactic functions in this manner.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] This question about what comes first (the functions or the constellation) is not an inflexible matter.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] The stances of both grammar types (dependency and phrase structure) are not narrowly limited to the traditional views.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Dependency and phrase structure are both fully compatible with both approaches to the syntactic functions.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] Indeed, monostratal systems, that are solely based on dependency or phrase structure, will likely reject the notion that the functions are derived from the constellation or that the constellation is derived from the functions.
[src:spacy-nlp/dependency-grammar] They will take both to be primitive, which means neither can be derived from the other.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] In computational linguistics, lemmatization is the algorithmic process of determining the lemma of a word based on its intended meaning.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] Unlike stemming, lemmatization depends on correctly identifying the intended part of speech and meaning of a word in a sentence, as well as within the larger context surrounding that sentence, such as neighbouring sentences or even an entire document.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] As a result, developing efficient lemmatization algorithms is an open area of research.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] In many languages, words appear in several *inflected* forms.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] For example, in English, the verb 'to walk' may appear as 'walk', 'walked', 'walks' or 'walking'.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] The base form, 'walk', that one might look up in a dictionary, is called the *lemma* for the word.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] The association of the base form with a part of speech is often called a *lexeme* of the word.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] Lemmatization is closely related to stemming.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] The difference is that a stemmer operates on a single word *without* knowledge of the context, and therefore cannot discriminate between words which have different meanings depending on part of speech.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] However, stemmers are typically easier to implement and run faster.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] The reduced "accuracy" may not matter for some applications.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] In fact, when used within information retrieval systems, stemming improves query recall accuracy, or true positive rate, when compared to lemmatization.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] Nonetheless, stemming reduces precision, or the proportion of positively-labeled instances that are actually positive, for such systems.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] The word "walk" is the base form for the word "walking", and hence this is matched in both stemming and lemmatization.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] The word "meeting" can be either the base form of a noun or a form of a verb ("to meet") depending on the context; e.g., "in our last meeting" or "We are meeting again tomorrow".
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] Unlike stemming, lemmatization attempts to select the correct lemma depending on the context.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] Document indexing software like Lucene can store the base stemmed format of the word without the knowledge of meaning, but only considering word formation grammar rules.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] The stemmed word itself might not be a valid word: 'lazy', as seen in the example below, is stemmed by many stemmers to 'lazi'.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] This is because the purpose of stemming is not to produce the appropriate lemma – that is a more challenging task that requires knowledge of context.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] The main purpose of stemming is to map different forms of a word to a single form.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] As a rule-based algorithm, dependent only upon the spelling of a word, it sacrifices accuracy to ensure that, for example, when 'laziness' is stemmed to 'lazi', it has the same stem as 'lazy'.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] A trivial way to do lemmatization is by simple dictionary lookup.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] This works well for straightforward inflected forms, but a rule-based system will be needed for other cases, such as in languages with long compound words.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] Such rules can be either hand-crafted or learned automatically from an annotated corpus.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] Morphological analysis of published biomedical literature can yield useful results.
[src:spacy-nlp/lemmatisation] Morphological processing of biomedical text can be more effective by a specialized lemmatization program for biomedicine, and may improve the accuracy of practical information extraction tasks.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] In this example, a person name consisting of one token, a two-token company name and a temporal expression have been detected and classified.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] In the expression *named entity*, the word *named* restricts the task to those entities for which one or many strings, such as words or phrases, stand (fairly) consistently for some referent.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] This is closely related to rigid designators, as defined by Saul Kripke, although in practice NER deals with many names and referents that are not philosophically "rigid".
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] For instance, the *automotive company created by Henry Ford in 1903* can be referred to as *Ford* or *Ford Motor Company*, although "Ford" can refer to many other entities as well (see Ford).
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Full named-entity recognition is often broken down, conceptually and possibly also in implementations, as two distinct problems: detection of names, and classification of the names by the type of entity they refer to (e.g. person, organization, or location).
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] The first phase is typically simplified to a segmentation problem: names are defined to be contiguous spans of tokens, with no nesting, so that "Bank of America" is a single name, disregarding the fact that inside this name, the substring "America" is itself a name.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] This segmentation problem is formally similar to chunking.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] The second phase requires choosing an ontology by which to organize categories of things.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Temporal expressions and some numerical expressions (e.g., money, percentages, etc.) may also be considered as named entities in the context of the NER task.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] While some instances of these types are good examples of rigid designators (e.g., the year 2001) there are also many invalid ones (e.g., I take my vacations in “June”).
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] In the first case, the year *2001* refers to the *2001st year of the Gregorian calendar*.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] In the second case, the month *June* may refer to the month of an undefined year (*past June*, *next June*, *every June*, etc.).
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] It is arguable that the definition of *named entity* is loosened in such cases for practical reasons.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] The definition of the term *named entity* is therefore not strict and often has to be explained in the context in which it is used.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Certain hierarchies of named entity types have been proposed in the literature.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] BBN categories, proposed in 2002, are used for *question answering* and consists of 29 types and 64 subtypes.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Sekine's extended hierarchy, proposed in 2002, is made of 200 subtypes.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] More recently, in 2011 Ritter used a hierarchy based on common Freebase entity types in ground-breaking experiments on NER over social media text.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] NER can have reference resolution ambiguities where the same name can refer to different entities of the same type.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] For example, "JFK" can refer to the former president of the United States or his son.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] The same name can refer to completely different types.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] "JFK" might refer to the airport in New York.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] "IRA" can refer to Individual Retirement Account, International Reading Association or Irish Republican Army.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] For example, "The White House" can refer to an organization instead of a location.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] To evaluate the quality of an NER system's output, several measures have been defined.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] The usual measures are called precision, recall, and F1 score.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] However, several issues remain in just how to calculate those values.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] These statistical measures work reasonably well for the obvious cases of finding or missing a real entity exactly; and for finding a non-entity.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] However, NER can fail in many other ways, many of which are arguably "partially correct", and should not be counted as complete success or failures.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] One overly simple method of measuring accuracy is merely to count what fraction of all tokens in the text were correctly or incorrectly identified as part of entity references (or as being entities of the correct type).
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] It follows from the above definition that any prediction that misses a single token, includes a spurious token, or has the wrong class, is a hard error and does not contribute positively to either precision or recall.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Thus, this measure may be said to be pessimistic: it can be the case that many "errors" are close to correct, and might be adequate for a given purpose.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] For example, one system might always omit titles such as "Ms." or "Ph.D.", but be compared to a system or ground-truth data that expects titles to be included.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] In that case, every such name is treated as an error.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Because of such issues, it is important actually to examine the kinds of errors, and decide how important they are given one's goals and requirements.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Evaluation models based on a token-by-token matching have been proposed.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Such models may be given partial credit for overlapping matches (such as using the Intersection over Union criterion).
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] They allow a finer grained evaluation and comparison of extraction systems.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] NER systems have been created that use linguistic grammar-based techniques as well as statistical models such as machine learning.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] State of the art systems may incorporate multiple approaches.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Hand-crafted grammar-based systems typically obtain better precision, but at the cost of lower recall and months of work by experienced computational linguists.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Statistical NER systems typically require a large amount of manually annotated training data.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Semisupervised approaches have been suggested to avoid part of the annotation effort.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] In the statistical learning era, NER was usually performed by learning a simple linear regression model on engineered features, then decoded by a bidirectional Viterbi algorithm.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] A **gazetteer** is a list of names and their types, such as "General Electric".
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] It can be used to augment any system for NER.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] They had been often used in the era of statistical machine learning.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Many different classifier types have been used to perform machine-learned NER, with conditional random fields being a typical choice.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Transformers features token classification using deep learning models.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Early work in NER systems in the 1990s was aimed primarily at extraction from journalistic articles.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Attention then turned to processing of military dispatches and reports.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Later stages of the automatic content extraction (ACE) evaluation also included several types of informal text styles, such as weblogs and text transcripts from conversational telephone speech conversations.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Since about 1998, there has been a great deal of interest in entity identification in the molecular biology, bioinformatics, and medical natural language processing communities.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] The most common entity of interest in that domain has been names of genes and gene products.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] There has been also considerable interest in the recognition of chemical entities and drugs in the context of the CHEMDNER competition, with 27 teams participating in this task.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] In 2001, research indicated that even state-of-the-art NER systems were brittle, meaning that NER systems developed for one domain did not typically perform well on other domains.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Considerable effort is involved in tuning NER systems to perform well in a new domain; this is true for both rule-based and trainable statistical systems.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] As of 2007, state-of-the-art NER systems for English produce near-human performance.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] For example, the best system entering MUC-7 scored 93.39% of F-measure while human annotators scored 97.60% and 96.95%.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Despite high F1 numbers reported on the MUC-7 dataset, the problem of named-entity recognition is far from being solved.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] The main efforts are directed to reducing the annotations labor by employing semi-supervised learning, robust performance across domains and scaling up to fine-grained entity types.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] In recent years, many projects have turned to crowdsourcing, which is a promising solution to obtain high-quality aggregate human judgments for supervised and semi-supervised machine learning approaches to NER.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Another challenging task is devising models to deal with linguistically complex contexts such as Twitter and search queries.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] There are some researchers who did some comparisons about the NER performances from different statistical models such as HMM (hidden Markov model), ME (maximum entropy), and CRF (conditional random fields), and feature sets.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] And some researchers recently proposed graph-based semi-supervised learning model for language specific NER tasks.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] A recently emerging task of identifying "important expressions" in text and cross-linking them to Wikipedia can be seen as an instance of extremely fine-grained named-entity recognition, where the types are the actual Wikipedia pages describing the (potentially ambiguous) concepts.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] Another field that has seen progress but remains challenging is the application of NER to Twitter and other microblogs, considered "noisy" due to non-standard orthography, shortness and informality of texts.
[src:spacy-nlp/named-entity-recognition] NER challenges in English Tweets have been organized by research communities to compare performances of various approaches, such as bidirectional LSTMs, Learning-to-Search, or CRFs.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Major processing tasks in an NLP system include: speech recognition, text classification, natural language understanding, and natural language generation.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Natural language processing has its roots in the 1950s.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Already in 1950, Alan Turing published an article titled "Computing Machinery and Intelligence," which proposed what is now called the Turing test as a criterion of intelligence, though at the time that was not articulated as a problem separate from artificial intelligence.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] The proposed test includes a task that involves the automated interpretation and generation of natural language.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Up until the 1980s, most natural language processing systems were based on complex sets of hand-written rules.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Starting in the late 1980s, however, there was a revolution in natural language processing with the introduction of machine learning algorithms for language processing.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Symbolic approach, i.e., the hand-coding of a set of rules for manipulating symbols, coupled with a dictionary lookup, was historically the first approach used both by AI in general and by NLP in particular: such as by writing grammars or devising heuristic rules for stemming.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] In the late 1980s and mid-1990s, the statistical approach ended a period of AI winter, which was caused by the inefficiencies of the rule-based approaches.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] The earliest decision trees, producing systems of hard if–then rules, were still very similar to the old rule-based approaches.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Only the introduction of hidden Markov models, applied to part-of-speech tagging, announced the end of the old rule-based approach.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] A major drawback of statistical methods is that they require elaborate feature engineering.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Since 2015, neural network–based methods have increasingly replaced traditional statistical approaches, using semantic networks and word embeddings to capture semantic properties of words.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Intermediate tasks (e.g., part-of-speech tagging and dependency parsing) are not needed anymore.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Neural machine translation, based on the then-newly invented sequence-to-sequence transformations, made obsolete the intermediate steps, such as word alignment, previously necessary for statistical machine translation.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] The following is a list of some of the most commonly researched tasks in natural language processing.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Some of these tasks have direct real-world applications, while others more commonly serve as subtasks that are used to aid in solving larger tasks.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Though natural language processing tasks are closely intertwined, they can be subdivided into categories for convenience.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given an image representing printed text, determine the corresponding text.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a sound clip of a person or people speaking, determine the textual representation of the speech.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] is a necessary subtask of speech recognition (see below).
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] to discrete characters can be a very difficult process.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Also, given that words in the same language are spoken by people with different accents, the speech recognition software must be able to recognize the wide variety of input as being identical to each other in terms of its textual equivalent.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a sound clip of a person or people speaking, separate it into words.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a text, transform those units and produce a spoken representation.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Text-to-speech can be used to aid the visually impaired.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] is a text-processing technique that divides text into individual words or word fragments.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] This technique results in two key components: a word index and tokenized text.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] The word index is a list that maps unique words to specific numerical identifiers, and the tokenized text replaces each word with its corresponding numerical token.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] These numerical tokens are then used in various deep learning methods.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] , this is fairly trivial, since words are usually separated by spaces.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] The task of removing inflectional endings only and returning the base dictionary form of a word which is also known as a lemma.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Lemmatization is another technique for reducing words to their normalized form.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] But in this case, the transformation actually uses a dictionary to map words to their actual form.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] and identify the class of the morphemes.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] , the structure of words) of the language being considered.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] , and thus it is often possible to ignore this task entirely and simply model all possible forms of a word (e.g., "open, opens, opened, opening") as separate words.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Indian language, however, such an approach is not possible, as each dictionary entry has thousands of possible word forms.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Many words, especially common ones, can serve as multiple parts of speech.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] ; and "out" can be any of at least five different parts of speech.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] The process of reducing inflected (or sometimes derived) words to a base form (e.g., "close" will be the root for "closed", "closing", "close", "closer" etc.).
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Stemming yields similar results as lemmatization, but does so on grounds of rules, not a dictionary.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a chunk of text, find the sentence boundaries.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] (grammatical analysis) of a given sentence.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] and typical sentences have multiple possible analyses: perhaps surprisingly, for a typical sentence there may be thousands of potential parses (most of which will seem completely nonsensical to a human).
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] What is the computational meaning of individual words in context?
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] How can we learn semantic representations from data?
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a stream of text, determine which items in the text map to proper names, such as people or places, and what the type of each such name is (e.g. person, location, organization).
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] , and in any case, is often inaccurate or insufficient.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] For example, the first letter of a sentence is also capitalized, and named entities often span several words, only some of which are capitalized.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Furthermore, many other languages in non-Western scripts (e.g.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] ) do not have any capitalization at all, and even languages with capitalization may not consistently use it to distinguish names.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] This task is also referred to as token classification.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Sentiment analysis involves identifying and classifying the emotional tone expressed in text.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] This technique involves analyzing text to determine whether the expressed sentiment is positive, negative, or neutral.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] models designed to recognize both long-term and short-term dependencies in text sequences.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] The applications of sentiment analysis are diverse, extending to tasks such as categorizing customer reviews on various online platforms.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] The goal of terminology extraction is to automatically extract relevant terms from a given corpus.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] ; we have to select the meaning which makes the most sense in context.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] ; here we have to select the entity (a famous individual, a location, a company, etc.) which is referred to in context.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a chunk of text, identify the relationships among named entities (e.g. who is married to whom).
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a sentence or larger chunk of text, determine which words ("mentions") refer to the same objects ("entities").
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] with the nouns or names to which they refer.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] This rubric includes several related tasks.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] structure of a connected text, i.e. the nature of the discourse relationships between sentences (e.g. elaboration, explanation, contrast).
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] in a chunk of text (e.g. yes–no question, content question, statement, assertion, etc.).
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Then, identify semantic roles that are not explicitly realized in the current sentence, classify them into arguments that are explicitly realized elsewhere in the text and those that are not specified, and resolve the former against the local text.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given two text fragments, determine if one being true entails the other, entails the other's negation, or allows the other to be either true or false.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a chunk of text, separate it into segments each of which is devoted to a topic, and identify the topic of the segment.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] and the relationship between the main and subsidiary argument, or the main and counter-argument within discourse.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Produce a readable summary of a chunk of text.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Often used to provide summaries of the text of a known type, such as research papers, articles in the financial section of a newspaper.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Grammatical error detection and correction involves a great bandwidth of problems on all levels of linguistic analysis (phonology/orthography, morphology, syntax, semantics, pragmatics).
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Grammatical error correction is impactful since it affects hundreds of millions of people who use or acquire English as a second language.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] It has thus been subject to a number of shared tasks since 2011.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] , this can now (2019) be considered a largely solved problem and is being marketed in various commercial applications.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Translate a text from a natural language into formal logic.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Automatically translate text from one human language to another.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] ", i.e. requiring all of the different types of knowledge that humans possess (grammar, semantics, facts about the real world, etc.) to solve properly.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Natural language understanding involves the identification of the intended semantic from the multiple possible semantics that can be derived from a natural language expression which usually takes the form of organized notations of natural language concepts.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Introduction and creation of language metamodels and ontologies are efficient but empirical solutions.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] , or subjective Yes/No vs. objective True/False is expected for the construction of a basis of semantics formalization.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Convert information from computer databases or semantic intents into readable human language.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Not an NLP task proper but an extension of natural language generation and other NLP tasks is the creation of full-fledged books.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] , marketed as a novel, contains sixty million words.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] , this is grounded on factual knowledge and based on text summarization.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] A Document AI platform sits on top of the NLP technology enabling users with no prior experience of artificial intelligence, machine learning or NLP to quickly train a computer to extract the specific data they need from different document types.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] NLP-powered Document AI enables non-technical teams to quickly access information hidden in documents, for example, lawyers, business analysts and accountants.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Computer systems intended to converse with a human.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a human-language question, determine its answer.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Typical questions have a specific right answer (such as "What is the capital of Canada?"), but sometimes open-ended questions are also considered (such as "What is the meaning of life?").
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a description of an image, generate an image that matches the description.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a description of a video, generate a video that matches the description.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Based on long-standing trends in the field, it is possible to extrapolate future directions of NLP.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Most higher-level NLP applications involve aspects that emulate intelligent behavior and apparent comprehension of natural language.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] More broadly speaking, the technical operationalization of increasingly advanced aspects of cognitive behavior represents one of the developmental trajectories of NLP(see trends among CoNLL shared tasks above).
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Cognition refers to "the mental action or process of acquiring knowledge and understanding through thought, experience, and the senses." Cognitive science is the interdisciplinary, scientific study of the mind and its processes.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Cognitive linguistics is an interdisciplinary branch of linguistics, combining knowledge and research from both psychology and linguistics.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Especially during the age of symbolic NLP, the area of computational linguistics maintained strong ties with cognitive studies.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Assign relative measures of meaning to a word, phrase, sentence or piece of text based on the information presented before and after the piece of text being analyzed, e.g., by means of a probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG).
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] Ties with cognitive linguistics are part of the historical heritage of NLP, but they have been less frequently addressed since the statistical turn during the 1990s.
[src:spacy-nlp/natural-language-processing] More recently, ideas of cognitive NLP have been revived as an approach to achieve explainability, e.g., under the notion of "cognitive AI".
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] In corpus linguistics, **part-of-speech tagging** (**POS tagging**, **PoS tagging**, or **POST**), also called **grammatical tagging**, is the process of marking up a word in a text (corpus) as corresponding to a particular part of speech, based on both its definition and its context.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] A simplified form of this is commonly taught to school-age children, in the identification of words as nouns, verbs, adjectives, adverbs, etc.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Once performed by hand, POS tagging is now done in the context of computational linguistics, using algorithms which associate discrete terms, as well as hidden parts of speech, by a set of descriptive tags.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] POS-tagging algorithms fall into two distinctive groups: rule-based and stochastic.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Brill's tagger, one of the first and most widely used English POS taggers, employs rule-based algorithms.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Part-of-speech tagging is harder than just having a list of words and their parts of speech, because some words can represent more than one part of speech at different times, and because some parts of speech are complex.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] This is not rare—in natural languages (as opposed to many artificial languages), a large percentage of word-forms are ambiguous.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Correct grammatical tagging will reflect that "dogs" is here used as a verb, not as the more common plural noun.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Schools commonly teach that there are 9 parts of speech in English: noun, verb, article, adjective, preposition, pronoun, adverb, conjunction, and interjection.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] However, there are clearly many more categories and sub-categories.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] For nouns, the plural, possessive, and singular forms can be distinguished.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] In many languages words are also marked for their "case" (role as subject, object, etc.), grammatical gender, and so on; while verbs are marked for tense, aspect, and other things.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] In some tagging systems, different inflections of the same root word will get different parts of speech, resulting in a large number of tags.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] For example, NN for singular common nouns, NNS for plural common nouns, NP for singular proper nouns (see the POS tags used in the Brown Corpus).
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Other tagging systems use a smaller number of tags and ignore fine differences or model them as features somewhat independent from part-of-speech.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] In part-of-speech tagging by computer, it is typical to distinguish from 50 to 150 separate parts of speech for English.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Work on stochastic methods for tagging Koine Greek (DeRose 1990) has used over 1,000 parts of speech and found that about as many words were ambiguous in that language as in English.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] A morphosyntactic descriptor in the case of morphologically rich languages is commonly expressed using very short mnemonics, such as *Ncmsan* for Category = Noun, Type = common, Gender = masculine, Number = singular, Case = accusative, Animate = no.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The most popular "tag set" for POS tagging for American English is probably the Penn tag set, developed in the Penn Treebank project.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] It is largely similar to the earlier Brown Corpus and LOB Corpus tag sets, though much smaller.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] In Europe, tag sets from the Eagles Guidelines see wide use and include versions for multiple languages.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] POS tagging work has been done in a variety of languages, and the set of POS tags used varies greatly with language.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Tags usually are designed to include overt morphological distinctions, although this leads to inconsistencies such as case-marking for pronouns but not nouns in English, and much larger cross-language differences.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The tag sets for heavily inflected languages such as Greek and Latin can be very large; tagging *words* in agglutinative languages such as Inuit languages may be virtually impossible.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] At the other extreme, Petrov et al. have proposed a "universal" tag set, with 12 categories (for example, no subtypes of nouns, verbs, punctuation, and so on).
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Whether a very small set of very broad tags or a much larger set of more precise ones is preferable, depends on the purpose at hand.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Automatic tagging is easier on smaller tag-sets.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Research on part-of-speech tagging has been closely tied to corpus linguistics.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The first major corpus of English for computer analysis was the Brown Corpus developed at Brown University by Henry Kučera and W.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] It consists of about 1,000,000 words of running English prose text, made up of 500 samples from randomly chosen publications.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Each sample is 2,000 or more words (ending at the first sentence-end after 2,000 words, so that the corpus contains only complete sentences).
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The Brown Corpus was painstakingly "tagged" with part-of-speech markers over many years.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] A first approximation was done with a program by Greene and Rubin, which consisted of a huge handmade list of what categories could co-occur at all.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] For example, article then noun can occur, but article then verb (arguably) cannot.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Its results were repeatedly reviewed and corrected by hand, and later users sent in errata so that by the late 70s the tagging was nearly perfect (allowing for some cases on which even human speakers might not agree).
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] This corpus has been used for innumerable studies of word-frequency and of part-of-speech and inspired the development of similar "tagged" corpora in many other languages.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Statistics derived by analyzing it formed the basis for most later part-of-speech tagging systems, such as CLAWS and VOLSUNGA.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] However, by this time (2005) it has been superseded by larger corpora such as the 100 million word British National Corpus, even though larger corpora are rarely so thoroughly curated.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] For some time, part-of-speech tagging was considered an inseparable part of natural language processing, because there are certain cases where the correct part of speech cannot be decided without understanding the semantics or even the pragmatics of the context.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] This is extremely expensive, especially because analyzing the higher levels is much harder when multiple part-of-speech possibilities must be considered for each word.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] In the mid-1980s, researchers in Europe began to use hidden Markov models (HMMs) to disambiguate parts of speech, when working to tag the Lancaster-Oslo-Bergen Corpus of British English.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] HMMs involve counting cases (such as from the Brown Corpus) and making a table of the probabilities of certain sequences.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] For example, once you've seen an article such as 'the', perhaps the next word is a noun 40% of the time, an adjective 40%, and a number 20%.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Knowing this, a program can decide that "can" in "the can" is far more likely to be a noun than a verb or a modal.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The same method can, of course, be used to benefit from knowledge about the following words.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] More advanced ("higher-order") HMMs learn the probabilities not only of pairs but triples or even larger sequences.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] So, for example, if you've just seen a noun followed by a verb, the next item may be very likely a preposition, article, or noun, but much less likely another verb.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] When several ambiguous words occur together, the possibilities multiply.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] However, it is easy to enumerate every combination and to assign a relative probability to each one, by multiplying together the probabilities of each choice in turn.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The combination with the highest probability is then chosen.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The European group developed CLAWS, a tagging program that did exactly this and achieved accuracy in the 93–95% range.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] CLAWS pioneered the field of HMM-based part of speech tagging but was quite expensive since it enumerated all possibilities.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] It sometimes had to resort to backup methods when there were simply too many options (the Brown Corpus contains a case with 17 ambiguous words in a row, and there are words such as "still" that can represent as many as 7 distinct parts of speech.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] HMMs underlie the functioning of stochastic taggers and are used in various algorithms one of the most widely used being the bi-directional inference algorithm.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Church independently developed dynamic programming algorithms to solve the same problem in vastly less time.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Their methods were similar to the Viterbi algorithm known for some time in other fields.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] DeRose used a table of pairs, while Church used a table of triples and a method of estimating the values for triples that were rare or nonexistent in the Brown Corpus (an actual measurement of triple probabilities would require a much larger corpus).
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Both methods achieved an accuracy of over 95%.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] DeRose's 1990 dissertation at Brown University included analyses of the specific error types, probabilities, and other related data, and replicated his work for Greek, where it proved similarly effective.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] These findings were surprisingly disruptive to the field of natural language processing.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The accuracy reported was higher than the typical accuracy of very sophisticated algorithms that integrated part of speech choice with many higher levels of linguistic analysis: syntax, morphology, semantics, and so on.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] CLAWS, DeRose's and Church's methods did fail for some of the known cases where semantics is required, but those proved negligibly rare.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] This convinced many in the field that part-of-speech tagging could usefully be separated from the other levels of processing; this, in turn, simplified the theory and practice of computerized language analysis and encouraged researchers to find ways to separate other pieces as well.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Markov Models became the standard method for the part-of-speech assignment.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The methods already discussed involve working from a pre-existing corpus to learn tag probabilities.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] It is, however, also possible to bootstrap using "unsupervised" tagging.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Unsupervised tagging techniques use an untagged corpus for their training data and produce the tagset by induction.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] That is, they observe patterns in word use, and derive part-of-speech categories themselves.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] For example, statistics readily reveal that "the", "a", and "an" occur in similar contexts, while "eat" occurs in very different ones.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] With sufficient iteration, similarity classes of words emerge that are remarkably similar to those human linguists would expect; and the differences themselves sometimes suggest valuable new insights.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] These two categories can be further subdivided into rule-based, stochastic, and neural approaches.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Some current major algorithms for part-of-speech tagging include the Viterbi algorithm, Brill tagger, Constraint Grammar, and the Baum-Welch algorithm (also known as the forward-backward algorithm).
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Hidden Markov model and visible Markov model taggers can both be implemented using the Viterbi algorithm.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] The rule-based Brill tagger is unusual in that it learns a set of rule patterns, and then applies those patterns rather than optimizing a statistical quantity.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Many machine learning methods have also been applied to the problem of POS tagging.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Methods such as SVM, maximum entropy classifier, perceptron, and nearest-neighbor have all been tried, and most can achieve accuracy above 95%.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] A direct comparison of several methods is reported (with references) at the ACL Wiki.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] This comparison uses the Penn tag set on some of the Penn Treebank data, so the results are directly comparable.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] However, many significant taggers are not included (perhaps because of the labor involved in reconfiguring them for this particular dataset).
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] Thus, it should not be assumed that the results reported here are the best that can be achieved with a given approach; nor even the best that *have* been achieved with a given approach.
[src:spacy-nlp/part-of-speech-tagging] In 2014, a paper reported using the structure regularization method for part-of-speech tagging, achieving 97.36% on a standard benchmark dataset.
[src:spacy-nlp/spacy] Using Thinc as its backend, spaCy features convolutional neural network models for part-of-speech tagging, dependency parsing, text categorization and named entity recognition (NER).
[src:spacy-nlp/spacy] Prebuilt statistical neural network models to perform these tasks are available for 23 languages, including English, Portuguese, Spanish, Russian and Chinese, and there is also a multi-language NER model.
[src:spacy-nlp/spacy] Additional support for tokenization for more than 65 languages allows users to train custom models on their own datasets as well.
